    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nEmacs has ability to remember the position when yanking and it puts to the same position while pasting a line, whereas Neovim puts the cursor to the beginning of the line. \n\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9fc5cd01-fc22-4724-a182-0c15d88cf9a6\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nKinda fixed this already, if it doesn't go beyond the design philosophy I'd be more than happy to open up a PR for the same 😅\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9f02712c-2341-4f84-905a-5a588da53cd3\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.13.0-dev-32e249d-dirty\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes, vim 9.1\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS \n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty \n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
    "closed_at": "2026-04-21T11:17:59Z",
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "This is definitely a feature request rather than a bug.\n\nWith that said currently location is determined by which paste keymap is used.\n`p` puts the cursor at before the new text while `gp` puts the cursor after the new text. Changing `p` would be a undesirable breaking change. \n\nI do see the desire for a keymap that does what you requested though, but I am not sure if there is a good keymap available to use. \n\nUsers can also implement this relatively easily themselves by remapping yank or using an autocmd to record position and creating a custom paste keymap.\n",
